 Charente-Maritime, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Frankrijk","Renty, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France":"Renty, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1223–1263":"1223–1263","1223–Female":"1223–Deceased","1225–1290":"1225–1290","1227–Female":"1227–Deceased","1206–1278":"1206–1278","1241–1298":"1241–1298","1191–1226":"1191–1226","1205–Female":"1205–Deceased","1206":"1206","1205":"1205","1227":"1227","1226":"1226","1225":"1225","1223":"1223","1278":"1278","1298":"1298","1241":"1241","1263":"1263","1191":"1191","1290":"1290","Preures, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France":"Preures, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France","Neulles, Charente-Maritime, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Neulles, Charente-Maritime, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France","Renty, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France":"Renty, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Renty","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Angel, Alicia, Bolivar, Francisco, Jorge, Juan, Julio, Magda, Manuel, Nydia, Virgen.","Spanish and Portuguese: most probably from <i>renta</i> ‘income’, ‘rental’. This name is common mainly in the Caribbean; it is rare in Spain."],"variants":[{"name":"Rentas","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Jose, Pedro, Ramonita, Angel, Juan, Manuel, Mario, Tomas, Aida, Armando, Blanca.","Spanish and Portuguese: plural form of   Renta  ."]}]},{"name":"Madeleine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The French form of the byname of a character in the New Testament, Mary <i>Magdalene</i> ‘Mary of Magdala’. Magdala was a village on Lake Galilee, a few miles north of Tiberias. The woman ‘which had been healed of evil spirits and infirmities’ (Luke 8:2) was given this name in the Bible to distinguish her from other bearers of the very common name   Mary .  It was widely accepted in Christian folk belief that she was the same person as the repentant sinner who washed Christ's feet with her tears in the previous chapter (Luke 7), but there is no support in the text for this identification."],"variants":[{"name":"Madaline","meanings":["The French form of the byname of a character in the New Testament, Mary <i>Magdalene</i> ‘Mary of Magdala’. Magdala was a village on Lake Galilee, a few miles north of Tiberias. The woman ‘which had been healed of evil spirits and infirmities’ (Luke 8:2) was given this name in the Bible to distinguish her from other bearers of the very common name   Mary .  It was widely accepted in Christian folk belief that she was the same person as the repentant sinner who washed Christ's feet with her tears in the previous chapter (Luke 7), but there is no support in the text for this identification."]},{"name":"Madeline","meanings":["A female name softened down from Magdalen. Compare the French Madeleine and Madelon; the Italian Maddalena; and the Spanish Madelena."]},{"name":"Madalene","meanings":["The French form of the byname of a character in the New Testament, Mary <i>Magdalene</i> ‘Mary of Magdala’. Magdala was a village on Lake Galilee, a few miles north of Tiberias. The woman ‘which had been healed of evil spirits and infirmities’ (Luke 8:2) was given this name in the Bible to distinguish her from other bearers of the very common name   Mary .  It was widely accepted in Christian folk belief that she was the same person as the repentant sinner who washed Christ's feet with her tears in the previous chapter (Luke 7), but there is no support in the text for this identification."]},{"name":"Madelene","meanings":["The French form of the byname of a character in the New Testament, Mary <i>Magdalene</i> ‘Mary of Magdala’. Magdala was a village on Lake Galilee, a few miles north of Tiberias. The woman ‘which had been healed of evil spirits and infirmities’ (Luke 8:2) was given this name in the Bible to distinguish her from other bearers of the very common name   Mary .  It was widely accepted in Christian folk belief that she was the same person as the repentant sinner who washed Christ's feet with her tears in the previous chapter (Luke 7), but there is no support in the text for this identification."]},{"name":"Madelaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Madeleine ."]},{"name":"Madoline","meanings":["Modern respelling of   Madeleine ."]},{"name":"Madlyn","meanings":["Modern variant of   Madeleine  , influenced by the productive suffix <i>-lyn</i>;  see  Lynn ."]},{"name":"Madelyn","meanings":["The French form of the byname of a character in the New Testament, Mary <i>Magdalene</i> ‘Mary of Magdala’. Magdala was a village on Lake Galilee, a few miles north of Tiberias. The woman ‘which had been healed of evil spirits and infirmities’ (Luke 8:2) was given this name in the Bible to distinguish her from other bearers of the very common name   Mary .  It was widely accepted in Christian folk belief that she was the same person as the repentant sinner who washed Christ's feet with her tears in the previous chapter (Luke 7), but there is no support in the text for this identification."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Madeleine de Renty was born in 1223, in Renty, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, Fran